text: Bobby Riggs became a professional tennis player back in 1939 at the age of 21.4 years before Billie Jean King was born.He beat  30 year old Margaret Court in a match weeks before his match with Billie Jean King  6-2,6-1.He didn't have anything to prove at his age,and actually did more to advance women in sports by staging the match  than  many Feminists could have.The spectacle he engineered  drew more people's attention to the issue of women's rights than  almost any of the various marches or protests by Feminists,too.Unfortunately,he's a man so Feminists aren't about to admit any of this.Feminists,being the opportunistic assholes they are,they're going to try to use this to trigger more antagonism between men and women like they always do,and to push the idea of the superiority of women over men.The same way they tried to use the revisionist history related by the recent Linda Lovelace biography of the same name to attempt to condemn the porn industry.

text: I don't know about every one else hating on the movie, but to me it just looks boring. It's a famous true story. I already know how it ends. There's no point in watching it. In other movies that are based on true stories, there's more to them. There's more elements to them that the film explores. This story is pretty cut and dry. Not a lot of elements to explore. And if I already know the ending to the story, it's going to be boring as hell to watch. Plus, the one "trope" that I hate in female lead movies is that all of them have that one scene where the insanely dumb, chauvinist bad guy makes some dumb comment undermining the female character, the female character then responds with a witty retort and then proceeds to beat the male character either physically or in whatever way they're competing. To me that's cringe inducing and horrendous writing. And this movie is pretty much that scene stretched out for 2 hours.

text: any film about this ?  "Karsten Braasch v the Williams Sisters During the 1998 Australian Open, sisters Serena and Venus Williams boasted that they could beat any man ranked outside the world's top 200. The challenge was accepted by Karsten Braasch, a German player ranked No 203 (his highest ranking was No 38). Before the matches, Braasch played a round of golf in the morning, drank a couple of beers, smoked a few cigarettes, and then played the Williams sisters for a set each, one after the other. He defeated Serena, 6-1, and Venus, 6-2. Serena said afterwards "I didn't know it would be that hard. I hit shots that would have been winners on the women's tour and he got to them easily."  In 1999 when Serena Williams was 18 and ranked 4th in the world, she re-opened the debate on whether women can compete with men in professional sport. The US Open champion believed she could take on and beat the best players in the men's game - she even applied for a wild card entry to take part in a men's singles event, the Eurocard Open, but this did not eventuate, mainly because she could not compete as she was not a man."

text: It sucked.  Was rather a joke that didn't tell the real story and the sad thing is it's supposed to make you think that it's telling the real story behind the scenes but it was pretty much SJW crap.  King has even admitted she struggled to beat Riggs who was 25 years older than her.  This admission doesn't mean men are inherently better than women and Riggs didn't even act like it did after the match and also admitted to struggling.  The impression I got from newstories and interviews in all the years since then, they remained who they were but the competition gave them respect for each other.  This, the truth, would have made a better story.  I was just a teen and have never been into sports when this match took place but I remember it and I gave it a chance despite some of its stars' (Silverman, you loon, I'm looking at you) reps for being PC police because done right, it would have been good but instead of being done right, it was SJW twiddle and not fairly balanced.  Don't get me wrong.  It would have been equally bad if it was one-sided the other way also and made King look like a clown instead of Riggs.  This was a real opportunity to promote equality while also showing that assumptions on both sides were wrong and arguments on both sides that had points -- instead it was biased dribble.  And was Margaret Court really that horrid?  For a movie with a bias towards the empowerment of women, it was really extremely catty towards her.  Very, very disappointing.  What a pity.  Hollywood is truly getting to be a $#*t pile not worth wasting your money on.

text: I will never understand how this event came to mean as much as it appears to mean to some people as a movement thing. Wasn't it really just a publicity stunt? I'm sure it had to feel like a personal victory for Billie Jean King for a minute, as there were probably doubts leading up to the match. After all, Bobby Riggs had beaten Margaret Court earlier that year in the same kind of publicity thing. But how did it become more than just a moral victory for Billie Jean King? Because people made it that? He was 55, and she was 30. This was 1973. He was at the top of his game 36 years earlier. She wasn't playing Ilie Nastase or John Newcombe. Would it be that big of a deal if Serena Williams were to beat Bjorn Borg in a match today? Sorry, I just don't get how it was a big deal to anybody - except maybe a somewhat marginal, moral  victory for Billie jean King.
